        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We wish to map the polarization in the core region of NGC1068. This region should show the transition from the disk, dominated by accretion, to the outflow region, and we expect to see the polarization closest to the nucleus perpendicular to that further out in the outflow region (aligned at PA ~60). We therefore need to obtain multiple resolution elements across this region, which has a total continuum flux density of ~60mJy spread over the circumnuclear disk and outflow (Figure 2). 

Based on protostars and star forming regions in our galaxy, we expect the polarized signal to be ~2% (possibly higher where the magnetic field is amplified in the outflow region). The band-7 continuum images of Garcia-Burillo et al. show that the mean surface brightness in a 0.45" beam is about 3mJy. This implies a polarized flux density of 60muJy/beam, detectable at 5-sigma in 4.2hr of on-source time, and a total time (according to the OT) of 9.4hr, above the 3hr minimum for polarization and observable in e.g. 3x3hr sessions. (Note that a 5-sigma detection is required as Ricean bias means that lower sigma detections may not be reliable.) NGC1068 has ample flux to self-calibrate, so dynamic range will not be an issue.

Our team has much experience with dealing with polarimetric data, and has the expertise to make the most of this new observing mode, which will require careful calibration and imaging.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>This is the only allowed mode for band-7 polarization. We only need continuum data.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The angular resolution is chosen to match existing band-7 continuum images that clearly resolve the nuclear region. The largest angular scale encompasses the extent of the circumnuclear disk.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
